{"type":"message","id":"d30eb974","parentId":"8cf83303","timestamp":"2026-07-09T00:14:31.925Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_476d68f8deb645eeabe0e20c","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/data/workspace/skills/perplexity-research/SKILL.md"},"partialArgs":"{\"path\": \"/data/workspace/skills/perplexity-research/SKILL.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"litellm","model":"vertex_ai/zai-org/glm-5-maas","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1783556061994,"responseId":"4edOaoe6G7-S6dgPqeLdoAI"}}
{"type":"message","id":"5ed2434b","parentId":"d30eb974","timestamp":"2026-07-09T00:14:31.960Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_476d68f8deb645eeabe0e20c","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: perplexity-research\nversion: 0.1.0\ndescription: Brain-augmented web research. Sends brain context about a topic to Perplexity, which searches the web with citations and returns what is NEW vs what the brain already knows. Use for entity enrichment, current-state checks, deal monitoring, and freshness deltas. NOT for simple URL fetches (use web_fetch) or brain-only queries (use gbrain query).\ntriggers:\n  - \"perplexity research\"\n  - \"perplexity-research\"\n  - \"what's new about\"\n  - \"current state of\"\n  - \"web research\"\n  - \"what changed about\"\n  - \"surface new developments\"\nmutating: true\nwrites_pages: true\nwrites_to:\n  - research/\n---\n\n# perplexity-research — Brain-Augmented Web Research\n\n> **Convention:** see [conventions/quality.md](../conventions/quality.md) for\n> citation rules; every claim from web research lands with a verifiable\n> citation, not a paraphrase.\n>\n> **Convention:** see [conventions/brain-first.md](../conventions/brain-first.md)\n> for the lookup chain. This skill ENFORCES brain-first by sending brain\n> context as part of the Perplexity prompt — the web search focuses on\n> the delta between brain knowledge and current web state.\n\n## What this does\n\nCombines existing brain knowledge with Perplexity's web search. The\nagent sends brain context about a topic into a Perplexity query;\nPerplexity searches + reads + synthesizes multiple pages with citations,\nfocused on what's NEW relative to the supplied context.\n\n**The key insight:** Perplexity doesn't just search — it reads and\nsynthesizes with citations. By sending brain context in the\ninstructions, it knows what you already know, so it surfaces the delta\ninstead of repeating settled fact.\n\n## When to use this vs other tools\n\n| Need | Use |\n|------|-----|\n| Deep research with citations | **This skill** — Perplexity + Opus |\n| Quick URL content | `web_fetch` |\n| Brain-only lookup | `gbrain query` / `gbrain search` |\n| Real-time social monitoring | external X / social-media collectors |\n| Structured data lookup against a tracker | `skills/data-research/SKILL.md` |\n\n## Output structure\n\nThe research output lands as a brain page under `research/<slug>.md` with\nthis structure:\n\n```markdown\n---\ntitle: \"[Topic] — Research [YYYY-MM-DD]\"\ntype: research\ndate: YYYY-MM-DD\nbrain_context_slugs: [\"pages whose context was sent to Perplexity\"]\nrecency_filter: \"[hour|day|week|month|none]\"\n---\n\n# [Topic] — Research [YYYY-MM-DD]\n\n> Executive summary: 2-3 sentences on the delta between brain knowledge\n> and current web state.\n\n## Key New Developments\nWhat's changed since the brain was last updated on this topic.\n\n## Confirming Signals\nWeb evidence validating existing brain knowledge.\n\n## Contradictions or Updates\nThings that conflict with the brain — these need a closer look.\n\n## Recommended Brain Updates\nSpecific page updates the user might want to make based on this research.\nEach item: which page, what to add or change, source URL.\n\n## Citations\n- [Source title](URL) — accessed YYYY-MM-DD\n- [Source title](URL) — accessed YYYY-MM-DD\n- ...\n```\n\n## Invocation\n\nThe skill is markdown agent instructions; the agent uses Perplexity's\nAPI directly (or a host-provided `perplexity` CLI if installed):\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pull brain context\ngbrain get <slug>                    # or\ngbrain query \"<topic keywords>\"\n\n# 2. Compose the Perplexity query with brain context inline:\n#    \"\"\"\n#    Topic: <topic>\n#    Brain context (what we already know): <embedded gbrain content>\n#    Find: what's NEW since 2026-MM-DD that the brain doesn't reflect.\n#    Cite every claim.\n#    \"\"\"\n\n# 3. Call Perplexity API or the host's perplexity binary:\n#    curl https://api.perplexity.ai/chat/completions \\\n#      -H \"Authorization: Bearer $PERPLEXITY_API_KEY\" \\\n#      -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n#      -d '{\"model\": \"sonar-pro\", \"messages\": [{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"...\"}]}'\n\n# 4. Write the structured research page via put_page:\ngbrain put_page research/<slug>      # via the put_page operation\n\n# 5. Cross-link entities mentioned (people, companies) per Iron Law.\n```\n\n## Models\n\n| Model | Cost / query | Use when |\n|-------|-------------|----------|\n| Perplexity sonar-pro | ~\\$0.04 | Deep analysis, entity enrichment, deal research |\n| Perplexity sonar | ~\\$0.007 | Quick lookups, bulk monitoring, briefing pipelines |\n\nDefault to sonar-pro. Drop to sonar for bulk / cron contexts where cost\nmatters more than depth.\n\n## Integration patterns\n\n### Entity enrichment\n\nCalled by `skills/enrich/SKILL.md` when an entity page (person, company)\nneeds current web context:\n\n```bash\nBRAIN=$(gbrain get people/<slug> 2>/dev/null)\n# Send <slug>'s page content as brain_context to Perplexity, get current\n# news / role / context, then update the brain page with what's new.\n```\n\n### Deal / company monitoring (cron)\n\nFor each active item under `deals/` or `companies/`:\n\n```bash\n# Weekly: pull recent news per company; flag changes for review.\n```\n\n### Morning briefing\n\nReplace raw `web_fetch` calls in briefing pipelines with this skill so\nthe agent doesn't re-narrate already-known facts.\n\n## Recency filter\n\nPass `recency_filter` to Perplexity: `hour | day | week | month`. Useful\nfor news-cycle topics; omit for evergreen research.\n\n## Anti-Patterns\n\n- ❌ Sending NO brain context. Then it's just a search — use `web_fetch`\n  instead.\n- ❌ Truncating the brain context. The whole point is \"knows what you\n  know.\" Send dense context.\n- ❌ Discarding citations. Every claim in the output must have a URL.\n- ❌ Skipping the cross-link step when entities are mentioned. Iron Law.\n\n## Environment\n\n- `PERPLEXITY_API_KEY` set in the agent's environment (or in\n  `~/.gbrain/.env`).\n- Optional: install Perplexity's official CLI for richer streaming output.\n\n## Related skills\n\n- `skills/academic-verify/SKILL.md` — wraps perplexity-research for\n  citation-verified academic claim checking\n- `skills/enrich/SKILL.md` — calls perplexity-research as part of the\n  entity-enrichment loop\n- `skills/data-research/SKILL.md` — structured-data trackers (different\n  shape: parameterized YAML recipes, not free-form research)\n\n\n## Contract\n\nThis skill guarantees:\n\n- Routing matches the canonical triggers in the frontmatter.\n- Output written under the directories listed in `writes_to:` (when applicable).\n- Conventions referenced (`quality.md`, `brain-first.md`, `_brain-filing-rules.md`) are followed.\n- Privacy contract preserved: no real names, no fork-specific filesystem path literals, no upstream-fork references.\n\nThe full behavior contract is documented in the body sections above; this section exists for the conformance test.\n\n## Output Format\n\nThe skill's output shape is documented inline in the body sections above (see \"Output\", \"Brain page format\", or equivalent). The literal section header here exists for the conformance test (`test/skills-conformance.test.ts`).\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1783556071952}}
{"type":"message","id":"79e61378","parentId":"5ed2434b","timestamp":"2026-07-09T00:14:42.666Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_923e0f0eb4dc400c8b4565a8","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/content-calendar.md"},"partialArgs":"{\"path\": \"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/content-calendar.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"litellm","model":"vertex_ai/zai-org/glm-5-maas","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1783556071983,"responseId":"7OdOauG-FIqM6dgPkLuekAM"}}
{"type":"message","id":"08a5ca82","parentId":"79e61378","timestamp":"2026-07-09T00:14:42.701Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_923e0f0eb4dc400c8b4565a8","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Content Calendar — Andrii Bidochko\n\n**Owner:** 264468965\n**Last updated:** 2026-07-06\n\n---\n\n## Scheduled Posts — Benchmark-First AI Agent Series\n\n### Post 1: The anatomy of a good benchmark (July 7, 9:00 AM UTC)\n\n**Pillar:** Technology & AI innovations\n**Key Message:** #4 — Benchmark-first AI Agent development\n**Status:** 📅 Scheduled for auto-publish\n\n**Draft:**\n\n𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘁𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗻 𝗮 𝗵𝗼𝗽𝗲𝗳𝘂𝗹 𝗔𝗜 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗷𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗮 𝘀𝗲𝗹𝗳-𝗲𝘃𝗼𝗹𝘃𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗼𝗻𝗲?\n\nOne has a benchmark. The other has vibes.\n\nA good benchmark answers three questions:\n\n1. **What's the task?** (specific, not vague)\n2. **What does \"done\" look like?** (verifiable outcome)\n3. **How do you measure it?** (quantifiable metric)\n\nMost teams skip this. They build the agent first, then scramble to figure out if it's working.\n\nFlip it. Write the benchmark BEFORE a single line of code. Make it pass. Then make the agent chase it.\n\nThe benchmark IS your reward function. Every iteration moves the needle. Every failure teaches the system.\n\nThis is TDD for AI. Test first. Agent second.\n\nWhat's one AI project you're building without a clear benchmark?\n\n#AI #AIAgents #TDD #MachineLearning #SoftwareEngineering\n\n**Characters:** ~950\n\n---\n\n### Post 2: Why most AI agents drift (July 7, 3:00 PM UTC)\n\n**Pillar:** Technology & AI innovations\n**Key Message:** #4 — Benchmark-first AI Agent development\n**Status:** ✅ Published — https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:share:7480274563235254272/\n\n**Draft:**\n\n𝗬𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗜 𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝘄𝗼𝗿𝗸𝘀 𝘁𝗼𝗱𝗮𝘆. 𝗜𝘁 𝗯𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗸𝘀 𝘁𝗼𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗿𝗼𝘄. 𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗱𝗼𝗻'𝘁 𝗸𝗻𝗼𝘄 𝘄𝗵𝘆.\n\nSound familiar?\n\nThis is the drift problem. Most agents have no anchor. They optimize for whatever feels right in the moment — but there's no fixed target.\n\nThe fix: **benchmark + reward function.**\n\nDefine the outcome. Make it measurable. Let the agent optimize toward it.\n\nEvery successful iteration is progress. Every failure is a signal. No guessing.\n\nTraditional software has tests. AI agents need benchmarks.\n\nWithout one, you're not building a system. You're building a feeling.\n\nWhat's your agent's benchmark — or are you hoping it figures itself out?\n\n#AI #AIAgents #MachineLearning #SoftwareEngineering #TDD\n\n**Characters:** ~900\n\n---\n\n## Trend Proposals — 2026-07-03\n\n### Claude Fable 5 outage exposed a fatal gap: only 1 in 10 enterprises can auto-catch failing AI\n**Source:** https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/enterprises-lost-claude-fable-5-for-a-few-weeks-new-data-shows-two-thirds-had-already-built-their-hedge\n**Published:** July 3, 2026\n**Pillar:** Technology & AI innovations\n**Angle:** \"The second-order effect nobody mentions\" — You built an AI agent. It went down. Did you even notice? Most teams have no fallback detection. That's the real risk.\n**Post hook draft:** 𝗬𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗜 𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝘄𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗱𝗼𝘄𝗻 𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘁 𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗸. 𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗱𝗶𝗱𝗻'𝘁 𝗻𝗼𝘁𝗶𝗰𝗲.\n**Persona:** CTO at 200+ person company — running production AI, can't afford silent failures\n**Status:** ✍️ Writing now\n\n---\n\n### Trunk Tools cut document review from 60 days to 10 — by ditching general-purpose models\n**Source:** https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/trunk-tools-cut-document-review-from-60-days-to-10-by-ditching-general-purpose-models\n**Published:** July 3, 2026\n**Pillar:** Technology & AI innovations\n**Angle:** \"The mistake most people will make\" — Most teams throw GPT-4 at everything. The winners are building specialized stacks that skip the bloat.\n**Post hook draft:** 𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗔𝗜 𝘀𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗸 𝗶𝘀𝗻'𝘁 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗲𝗹. 𝗜𝘁'𝘀 𝘇𝗲𝗿𝗼 𝗯𝗹𝗼𝗮𝘁.\n**Persona:** CTO at IT consultancy — needs to deliver client projects faster with reusable components\n**Scheduled:** July 7, 2026 (Monday)\n**Status:** Proposed 🔎\n\n---\n\n### DeepSeek open-sourced DSpark — 85% faster LLM inference\n**Source:** https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/deepseek-open-sources-dspark-a-new-framework-to-speed-up-llm-inference-by-up-to-85\n**Published:** June 29, 2026\n**Pillar:** Technology & AI innovations\n**Angle:** \"What this means for you\" — Inference costs are collapsing. If your AI strategy depends on one provider's pricing, you're overpaying. Open-source is eating the margin.\n**Post hook draft:** 𝗜𝗻𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝘀𝘁𝘀 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝗯𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗰𝗼𝗹𝗹𝗮𝗽𝘀𝗲.\n**Persona:** Founder/CEO at SMB — wants AI competitiveness without bleeding budget\n**Scheduled:** July 10, 2026 (Thursday)\n**Status:** Proposed 🔎\n\n---\n\n### Morgan Stanley made its AI agents LESS autonomous — and cut riskiest job in half\n**Source:** https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/morgan-stanley-cut-its-riskiest-reconciliation-job-in-half-by-making-its-agents-less-autonomous\n**Published:** June 30, 2026\n**Pillar:** Technology & AI innovations\n**Angle:** \"Contrarian take\" — Everyone's chasing fully autonomous agents. Morgan Stanley went the opposite direction — and won. Sometimes constraints beat freedom.\n**Post hook draft:** 𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗴𝗮𝗻 𝗦𝘁𝗮𝗻𝗹𝗲𝘆'𝘀 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗔𝗜 𝘄𝗶𝗻? 𝗠𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗼𝗺𝗼𝘂𝘀.\n**Persona:** Enterprise Innovation Officer at financial services company — zero tolerance for error, needs reliable AI\n**Status:** Proposed 🔎\n\n---\n\n### Restaurants now take orders from ChatGPT and Claude directly — no app, no setup\n**Source:** https://venturebeat.com/technology/restaurants-can-now-accept-orders-placed-directly-from-chatgpt-and-claude-thanks-to-squares-new-low-fee-no-setup-integration\n**Published:** July 1, 2026\n**Pillar:** Technology & AI innovations\n**Angle:** \"What this means for you\" — AI agents are now ordering dinner. Your customers will expect the same from your business. The question isn't if — it's how fast you can plug in.\n**Post hook draft:** 𝗖𝗵𝗮𝘁𝗚𝗣𝗧 𝗷𝘂𝘀𝘁 𝗼𝗿𝗱𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗻𝗲𝗿. 𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁'𝘀 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗲𝘅𝗰𝘂𝘀𝗲?\n**Persona:** Founder/CEO at SMB — needs to stay competitive with AI integration\n**Status:** Proposed 🔎\n\n---\n\n## Published Posts\n\n- 2026-07-06: Test-driven development changed how we write software (TDD ↔ Benchmark for AI Agents)\n- 2026-07-03: Alibaba just cut AI agent token use by 99%\n- 2026-06-25: Most companies are building AI backwards\n- 2026-06-25: AI isn't coming for your job\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1783556082698}}
{"type":"message","id":"56a2ab50","parentId":"08a5ca82","timestamp":"2026-07-09T00:15:09.051Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_37c544a062944bbc840eda4f","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"---\ndate: 2026-07-09\nn: 1\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/deepseek-open-sources-dspark-a-new-framework-to-speed-up-llm-inference-by-up-to-85\nsource_date: 2026-06-29\nstatus: pending\n---\n\n𝗜𝗻𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝘀𝘁𝘀 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝗯𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗰𝗼𝗹𝗹𝗮𝗽𝘀𝗲.\n\nDeepSeek just open-sourced DSpark — a framework that speeds up LLM inference by 85%.\n\nHere's why this matters for you.\n\nMost teams built their AI stack around one provider's pricing. OpenAI. Anthropic. Google. You locked in. Now you're paying their margins.\n\nBut inference costs aren't fixed. They're collapsing. Every month, open-source gets faster, cheaper, more competitive.\n\nThe gap between \"I need GPT-4\" and \"I can run this locally\" is shrinking fast.\n\nIf your AI strategy depends on one provider staying expensive — you're betting against the market.\n\nThe winners aren't the ones with the biggest AI budget. They're the ones who can swap models without rewriting their stack.\n\nThat's the real moat: flexibility, not spending power.\n\nWhen did you last price-check your inference costs?\n\n#AI #LLM #Inference #OpenSource #AIAgents\n","path":"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/pending/2026-07-09-draft-1.md"},"partialArgs":"{\"content\": \"---\\ndate: 2026-07-09\\nn: 1\\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/deepseek-open-sources-dspark-a-new-framework-to-speed-up-llm-inference-by-up-to-85\\nsource_date: 2026-06-29\\nstatus: pending\\n---\\n\\n𝗜𝗻𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝘀𝘁𝘀 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝗯𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗰𝗼𝗹𝗹𝗮𝗽𝘀𝗲.\\n\\nDeepSeek just open-sourced DSpark — a framework that speeds up LLM inference by 85%.\\n\\nHere's why this matters for you.\\n\\nMost teams built their AI stack around one provider's pricing. OpenAI. Anthropic. Google. You locked in. Now you're paying their margins.\\n\\nBut inference costs aren't fixed. They're collapsing. Every month, open-source gets faster, cheaper, more competitive.\\n\\nThe gap between \\\"I need GPT-4\\\" and \\\"I can run this locally\\\" is shrinking fast.\\n\\nIf your AI strategy depends on one provider staying expensive — you're betting against the market.\\n\\nThe winners aren't the ones with the biggest AI budget. They're the ones who can swap models without rewriting their stack.\\n\\nThat's the real moat: flexibility, not spending power.\\n\\nWhen did you last price-check your inference costs?\\n\\n#AI #LLM #Inference #OpenSource #AIAgents\\n\", \"path\": \"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/pending/2026-07-09-draft-1.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_eb1d65e28b8f4e229db80a4c","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"---\ndate: 2026-07-09\nn: 2\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/trunk-tools-cut-document-review-from-60-days-to-10-by-ditching-general-purpose-models\nsource_date: 2026-07-03\nstatus: pending\n---\n\n𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗔𝗜 𝘀𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗸 𝗶𝘀𝗻'𝘁 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗲𝗹. 𝗜𝘁'𝘀 𝘇𝗲𝗿𝗼 𝗯𝗹𝗼𝗮𝘁.\n\nTrunk Tools just cut document review from 60 days to 10.\n\nTheir secret? They stopped throwing GPT-4 at everything.\n\nHere's the mistake most teams make:\n\nYou pick a model. Then you try to make it do EVERYTHING. Summarization. Extraction. Classification. Generation. One tool, all jobs.\n\nThat's not a strategy. That's a crutch.\n\nThe winners are doing the opposite. They're building specialized stacks:\n→ Small models for simple tasks (fast, cheap)\n→ Domain-specific fine-tunes for niche work\n→ General-purpose models ONLY when nothing else fits\n\nThe result? 6x faster. 80% less spend. Better accuracy.\n\nYou don't need a bigger model. You need the RIGHT model for each job.\n\nWhat's one task you're overpaying to run?\n\n#AI #EnterpriseAI #LLM #AIArchitecture #Efficiency\n","path":"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/pending/2026-07-09-draft-2.md"},"partialArgs":"{\"content\": \"---\\ndate: 2026-07-09\\nn: 2\\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/trunk-tools-cut-document-review-from-60-days-to-10-by-ditching-general-purpose-models\\nsource_date: 2026-07-03\\nstatus: pending\\n---\\n\\n𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗔𝗜 𝘀𝘁𝗮𝗰𝗸 𝗶𝘀𝗻'𝘁 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗺𝗼𝗱𝗲𝗹. 𝗜𝘁'𝘀 𝘇𝗲𝗿𝗼 𝗯𝗹𝗼𝗮𝘁.\\n\\nTrunk Tools just cut document review from 60 days to 10.\\n\\nTheir secret? They stopped throwing GPT-4 at everything.\\n\\nHere's the mistake most teams make:\\n\\nYou pick a model. Then you try to make it do EVERYTHING. Summarization. Extraction. Classification. Generation. One tool, all jobs.\\n\\nThat's not a strategy. That's a crutch.\\n\\nThe winners are doing the opposite. They're building specialized stacks:\\n→ Small models for simple tasks (fast, cheap)\\n→ Domain-specific fine-tunes for niche work\\n→ General-purpose models ONLY when nothing else fits\\n\\nThe result? 6x faster. 80% less spend. Better accuracy.\\n\\nYou don't need a bigger model. You need the RIGHT model for each job.\\n\\nWhat's one task you're overpaying to run?\\n\\n#AI #EnterpriseAI #LLM #AIArchitecture #Efficiency\\n\", \"path\": \"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/pending/2026-07-09-draft-2.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a761f8ba23464736b36945b9","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"---\ndate: 2026-07-09\nn: 3\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/morgan-stanley-cut-its-riskiest-reconciliation-job-in-half-by-making-its-agents-less-autonomous\nsource_date: 2026-06-30\nstatus: pending\n---\n\n𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗴𝗮𝗻 𝗦𝘁𝗮𝗻𝗹𝗲𝘆'𝘀 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗔𝗜 𝘄𝗶𝗻? 𝗠𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗼𝗺𝗼𝘂𝘀.\n\nEveryone's chasing fully autonomous AI agents. Self-driving workflows. Zero human input.\n\nMorgan Stanley went the opposite direction. And it worked.\n\nTheir riskiest reconciliation job? Cut in half. Not by giving agents MORE freedom. By giving them constraints.\n\nHere's the insight most teams miss:\n\nAutonomy isn't a feature. It's a risk multiplier.\n\nThe more freedom an agent has, the more ways it can fail. The harder it is to debug. The less predictable the output.\n\nMorgan Stanley didn't dumb down their AI. They made it focused. Scoped. Accountable.\n\nThe result? Fewer errors. Faster resolution. Actual trust from the humans in the loop.\n\nSometimes the best AI architecture is knowing when to say \"stop, ask a human.\"\n\nAre your agents autonomous — or just unsupervised?\n\n#AI #AIAgents #EnterpriseAI #FinancialServices #Automation\n","path":"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/pending/2026-07-09-draft-3.md"},"partialArgs":"{\"content\": \"---\\ndate: 2026-07-09\\nn: 3\\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/morgan-stanley-cut-its-riskiest-reconciliation-job-in-half-by-making-its-agents-less-autonomous\\nsource_date: 2026-06-30\\nstatus: pending\\n---\\n\\n𝗠𝗼𝗿𝗴𝗮𝗻 𝗦𝘁𝗮𝗻𝗹𝗲𝘆'𝘀 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗔𝗜 𝘄𝗶𝗻? 𝗠𝗮𝗸𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁𝘀 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗮𝘂𝘁𝗼𝗻𝗼𝗺𝗼𝘂𝘀.\\n\\nEveryone's chasing fully autonomous AI agents. Self-driving workflows. Zero human input.\\n\\nMorgan Stanley went the opposite direction. And it worked.\\n\\nTheir riskiest reconciliation job? Cut in half. Not by giving agents MORE freedom. By giving them constraints.\\n\\nHere's the insight most teams miss:\\n\\nAutonomy isn't a feature. It's a risk multiplier.\\n\\nThe more freedom an agent has, the more ways it can fail. The harder it is to debug. The less predictable the output.\\n\\nMorgan Stanley didn't dumb down their AI. They made it focused. Scoped. Accountable.\\n\\nThe result? Fewer errors. Faster resolution. Actual trust from the humans in the loop.\\n\\nSometimes the best AI architecture is knowing when to say \\\"stop, ask a human.\\\"\\n\\nAre your agents autonomous — or just unsupervised?\\n\\n#AI #AIAgents #EnterpriseAI #FinancialServices #Automation\\n\", \"path\": \"/data/workspace/social/linkedin/264468965/pending/2026-07-09-draft-3.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"litellm","model":"vertex_ai/zai-org/glm-5-maas","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1783556082722,"responseId":"9-dOaqmAJb-S6dgPqeLdoAI"}}
